    <subsection>
        <title>Definitions</title>
        <p>
            In this section we discovered two families of semiregular polygons, 
            prisms and antiprisms. We can also create prisms and antiprisms which  
            have faces are not regular. In particular, the sides of a prism need not be  
            squares, they could be rectangles or other parallelograms. The sides of an 
            antiprism do not need to be equilateral. Moreover, the bases of a prism or antiprism may 
            be any polygon whatsoever.
        </p>
        <definition xml:id="def-prism">
            <idx>prism</idx>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A <term>prism</term> is a polyhedron consisting of two congruent parallel  
                    polygonal faces joined by sides that are parallelograms (often rectangles).
                </p>
            </statement> 
        </definition>
        <definition xml:id="def-antiprism">
            <idx>antiprism</idx>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    An <term>antiprism</term> is a polyhedron consisting of a 
                    pair of parallel congruent  
                    polygonal faces joined by sides that are triangles.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </definition>
        <p>
            The two parallel congruent polygonal faces are called the <term>bases</term> 
            of the prism or antiprism. The top base may be called the <term>summit</term>  
            in which case the bottom would be called the <term>base</term>. Of course, we  
            can sit a polyhedron on any of its faces. Sometimes the bases will be at the ends 
            rather than at the top and bottom.
            <idx><h>base</h><h>prism</h></idx>
            <idx><h>summit</h><h>prism</h></idx>
            <idx><h>base</h><h>antiprism</h></idx>
            <idx><h>summit</h><h>antiprism</h></idx>
        </p>
    </subsection>
